\begin_layout Subsection
General considerations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solvent molecules are rigids and the density is considered as depending
 of the position 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{r}$
\end_inset

 and the orientation 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Omega}$
\end_inset

 (in term of three Euler angles (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta,\phi,\psi$
\end_inset

).
 It can be shown that for a given external potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{ext}$
\end_inset

 , the Helmoltz free energy can be written as an unique exact functional
 of the solvent density, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal F}[\rho(\bm{r,\Omega})]$
\end_inset

.
 This functional can be split into three terms:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\cal F}[\rho]={\cal F}_{id}[\rho]+{\cal F}_{ext}[\rho]+{\cal F}_{exc}[\rho].\label{eq:F_decomp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first term is the ideal term, of the ideal fluid, and it can be computed
 using the following expression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\cal F}_{id}[\rho]=k_{B}T\int\int\left[\rho(\bm{r},\Omega)\ln(\frac{8\pi^{2}\rho(\bm{r},\Omega)}{n_{0}})-\rho(\bm{r},\Omega)+\frac{n_{0}}{8\pi^{2}}\right]d\bm{r}d\Omega.\label{eq:F_id}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

 is the thermal energy, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the homogeneous pure fluid density.
 The second term is the external one, it is due to interaction with the
 external potential, in this publication this term is due to the solute.
 It can be evaluated with the following expression, for any solute that
 is represented by an atomistic forcefield which create an external potential
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{ext}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\cal F}_{ext}[\rho]=k_{B}T\int\int\left[\rho(\bm{r},\Omega)V_{ext}(\bm{r},\Omega)\right]d\bm{r}d\Omega.\label{eq:F_ext}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third term is the complicated one, it is the excess term and is due
 to solvent-solvent interactions.
 In the homogeneous reference fluid approximation (HRF), we write the excess
 term as depending of the exact direct correlation function of the pure
 solvent.
 That approximation consist in making the hypothesis that the solvent, in
 the presence of the perturbation of the solute, possess the same correlation
 function,
\begin_inset Formula $c(|\bm{r-r'}|,\Omega,\Omega')$
\end_inset

 than the homogeneous solvent.
 Under this approximation the excess term can be written:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\cal F}_{exc}[\rho]=-\frac{1}{2}k_{B}T\int\int\Delta\rho(\bm{r},\Omega)c(|\bm{r-r'}|,\Omega,\Omega')\Delta\rho(\bm{r},\Omega)d\bm{r}d\bm{r'}d\Omega d\Omega'+{\cal F}_{B}[\rho],\label{eq:F_exc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\rho(\bm{r},\Omega)=\rho(\bm{r},\Omega)-n_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal F}[\rho]$
\end_inset

 is the correction to that approximation, i.e it is defined as the difference
 between the the exact value of the excess part and the first term.
 Physically it is the correction to that approximation and it can be expressed
 as an expansion of the solvent correlations depending on the multibody
 correlation functions.
 Some approximations of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bridge functionnal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 had been given in previous publications, for the sake of clarity we will
 suppose in this work that this term is null, which is a crude approximation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This expression was already implemented in previous publications.
 In the next subsections we will present a re-writting of this excess term
 as a functional of two simpler fields, the one particle solvent density
 
\begin_inset Formula $n(\bm{r})$
\end_inset

 and the polarization field 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{P(r)}$
\end_inset

, instead of the total solvent density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\bm{r},\Omega)$
\end_inset

.
 In a first part, we will consider a Polarization field limitated at the
 dipolar order, the one generated by making the approximation that solvent
 molecule can be represented by a pure dipole.
 In a second part we will consider the multipolar polarization field, i.e
 the one generated by a non-strictly dipolar charge distribution in the
 solvent.
\end_layout

